<div id="review_154936061" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/154936061" />
    <a title="Scott Ford" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3231469-scott-ford"><img alt="Scott Ford" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1265088695p2/3231469.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/154936061?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott Ford" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott Ford" href="/user/show/3231469-scott-ford">Scott Ford</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3231469-scott-ford?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer154936061" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5653304280085989529">Umberto Eco intellectualizes within the restraints of 17th century knowledge and superstition about the physics of the earth&apos;s rotation, natural phenomena, life, death, and love- which makes for an interesting thought-experiment, but becomes tedious for any reader living in the 21st century with more than a high-school education. The story follows a young man trapped on a 17th century ship in the lagoon of an island (Solomon Island, perhaps). Between the ship and the island supposedly runs the p</span>
  <span id="freeText5653304280085989529" style="display:none">Umberto Eco intellectualizes within the restraints of 17th century knowledge and superstition about the physics of the earth's rotation, natural phenomena, life, death, and love- which makes for an interesting thought-experiment, but becomes tedious for any reader living in the 21st century with more than a high-school education. The story follows a young man trapped on a 17th century ship in the lagoon of an island (Solomon Island, perhaps). Between the ship and the island supposedly runs the prime meridian, thus separating the two, timewise placing the island in the day before ship. In Foucault’s Pendulum, the author's explanations of the occult and macabre belief systems tied more succinctly into the novel's plot. Here, the sidebar intellectualizing of the characters as the story unfolds seems like the author's goal in and of itself, rendering the plot secondary to the accomplishment of producing intellectual debate limited to knowledge available during the 17th century. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5653304280085989529" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


